<font color="#FF0000">REFLECTIONS, GOOD AND BAD</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 13 21:29:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Classlass,<br><br>
For a child who wants you to speak, refusal to do so may cause just as much pain as the stories.  You may be correct.  My youngest is a military history buff.  Ancient to present.  He was classically trained in a Japanese university to have a deep appreciation of gaming theory, war, warriors, and trained in the ancient weapons.  They honor their warriors.  He approached me to talk about the war, forced me to tell stories.  He wanted to know.<br><br>
His older brother never asked and I never offered. I had uniforms tailored for them in Nam with all insignia.  He and his brother wore them everywhere.  It made them the center of attention in any crowd.  My wife says he was my spokesman and puffed out his chest and told them what his dad was doing.  Got him an up front ride with Delta Airlines on one trip.<br><br>
He without asking has retraced my steps around the world.  Made it a point to stand on the same spots I took pictures and take his own.  He just returned from SE Asia.  He has future plans to backpack across Vietnam and Cambodia.  He currently lives in Korea.  He is a photographer and through his lens I will do what I never did, return.  I have asked him to stay away from the jungles of South America.  I hope he listens.<br><br>
You asked.<br><br>
Who is the &quot;they&quot; you refer to when you say, &quot;they ask for reconciliation, or a common ground. The sacrifice must be theirs.  We have made ours.&quot; And.. What sacrifices can they make to bring about reconciliation?<br><br>
I confess I am guilty of generalization.  &quot;They&quot; are those who post here and wish us to see the world through their eyes.  They who resisted the war and generally detest the military regime and the human element that are attached to it.  They are the socialist harbingers who beat their chests in public display and preach beating weapons into plowshares.  They are the ones our society gives an audience, not the warrior.  What Cook calls and I agree &quot;Commies&quot;. The warrior is seen not heard, used not maintained, discarded not remembered.<br><br>
I am sure hospitals did their part, but I didn't see it.  Case in point.  In to the Doc with blood running from my sinuses.  I had decompression at altitude.  Just wanted some Afrin.  Sent to a shrink to see why I was afraid to fight.  He learned what I wasn't afraid to call him.  Experienced the old booby trap trip.  Doc's patched up the front parts.  A rare blood type and no blood put me on the possible endangered list.  Nurse to stay with me so I wouldn't be alone.  She discovered that no one had rolled me over.  She picked debris out of my back all night long. (I still think she is an angel).  A damn hospital type accused me of allowing myself to be injured and proceeded to process line of duty paperwork.  My buddies and the attending surgeon dressed my wounds, pulled out the I V, in uniform with weapon and returned to duty before that sanctimonious asshole returned (24 hours off duty).  They had to promise to keep me out of harms way until my blood count recovered.  Guys thought I was superman. (I thought I was dead).  Went to the hospital to get some dental floss.  Told them I had a popcorn kernel that was distracting me.  Yanked out the tooth, packed my mouth, and out to fly.  Low pressure makes you bleed like a stuck pig.  Pissed off the crew chief.  I became so afraid of the hospital that with the help of the Doc I flew missions during one tour with broken bones.  There are other worse stories.  <br><br>
I know there was a lot done right, but there were some incredible wrongs.  I wouldn't doubt Joe's story for minute.<br><br>
No reflection on those such as you who did their part.
<p><code>--   (SW) </code><p>


